            <pb n="2" facs="#f0001"/>
            <div n="1">
                <head>
                    <hi rendition="#k">Beautiful Extract.</hi>
                </head>
                <p>We possess a genuine<lb break="yes"/>fragment which Cicero has preserved to us
                    from a<lb break="yes"/>lost work of Aristotle. It runs thus: &#x201C;If there
                        were<lb break="yes"/>beings who lived in the depths of the earth, in
                        dwel-<lb break="no"/>lings adorned with statues and paintings, and every-<lb
                        break="no"/>thing which is possessed in rich abundance by those<lb
                        break="yes"/>whom we esteem fortunate, and if these beings could<lb
                        break="yes"/>receive tidings of the power and might of the gods,<lb
                        break="yes"/>and could then emerge from their hidden dwellings<lb
                        break="yes"/>through the open fissures of the earth, to the places<lb
                        break="yes"/>which we inhabit; if they could suddenly behold the<lb
                        break="yes"/>earth, and the sea, and the vault of heaven; could<lb
                        break="yes"/>recognize the expanse of the cloudy firmament and<lb
                        break="yes"/>the might of the winds of heaven, and admire the sun<lb
                        break="yes"/>in its majesty, beauty, and radiant effulgence; and,<lb
                        break="yes"/>lastly, when night veiled the earth in darkness, they<lb
                        break="yes"/>could behold the starry heavens, the changing moon,<lb
                        break="yes"/>and the stars rising and setting in the unvarying<lb
                        break="yes"/>course ordained from eternity; they would surely ex-<lb
                        break="no"/>claim, there are Gods, and such great things must be<lb
                        break="yes"/>the work of their hands.&#x201D;</p>
                <lb break="yes"/>
                <p>It has been justly observed, that this passage is<lb break="yes"/>alone
                    sufficient to corroborate Cicero&#x2019;s opinion of the<lb break="yes"
                    />&#x201C;golden flow of Aristotle&#x2019;s eloquence,&#x201D; and that his<lb
                        break="yes"/>works are pervaded by something of the inspired force<lb
                        break="yes"/>of Plato&#x2019;s genius. Such a testimony to the existence<lb
                        break="yes"/>of the heavenly powers, drawn from the beauty and<lb
                        break="yes"/>stupendous greatness of the works of creation, is<lb
                        break="yes"/>rarely to be met with in the works of antiquity.</p>
                <lb break="yes"/>
                <hi rendition="#et">
                    <hi rendition="#i"><choice><sic>Hnmboldt</sic><corr type="editorial"
                                >Humboldt</corr></choice>&#x2019;s Cosmos.</hi>
                </hi>
            </div>
